<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="active-listening">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>comms</group>
    <domain>communicator</domain>
    <summary>A structured listening practice (RASA: Receive, Appreciate, Summarize, Ask) that ensures the speaker feels understood before responding, combining paraphrasing, mirroring, and empathic reflection.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>listening</tag>
      <tag>rasa</tag>
      <tag>empathy</tag>
      <tag>requirements-gathering</tag>
      <tag>communication</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Active Listening</title>
    <summary>A structured listening practice (RASA: Receive, Appreciate, Summarize, Ask) that ensures the speaker feels understood before the listener responds. Combines paraphrasing, mirroring, open questions, and empathic reflection to reach Level 5 empathic listening — understanding both content and emotion.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>People who don't feel heard withhold information, resist decisions, and disengage. Active listening is the single highest-leverage technique for requirements gathering and conflict de-escalation: it costs nothing and directly reduces the "missing information" failure mode. Research shows 80% of communication problems trace to listening failures, not speaking failures.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Requirements gathering sessions with stakeholders or clients</item>
        <item>1-on-1 meetings where trust or engagement is at risk</item>
        <item>Customer discovery interviews (especially with skeptical interviewees)</item>
        <item>Conflict situations where one party feels misunderstood</item>
        <item>Performance discussions or coaching conversations</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Real-time agent conversations — agents cannot perform empathic listening live; they can scaffold it but not execute it</item>
        <item>High-stakes interpersonal conflicts — a script-driven approach risks feeling mechanical and backfiring</item>
        <item>Situations where a direct answer is needed and the other party is not emotionally engaged</item>
        <item>Asynchronous text threads where silence and pace cues are absent</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="RASA Framework">
      <rule>
        <statement>Work through all four RASA steps in every substantive conversation: Receive (full attention), Appreciate (acknowledgment), Summarize (reflect back), Ask (open follow-up).</statement>
        <rationale>Skipping Summarize is the most common failure — without paraphrasing, the speaker cannot confirm their message was understood and will either repeat or withhold detail.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Requirements session with a skeptical stakeholder.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[R: No phone, eye contact, note-taking only.
A: "I see", nods, "Go on..."
S: "So if I understand you, the current process takes 4 hours
    because the data export step is manual — is that right?"
A: "Can you walk me through what happens after the export?"]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Open vs Closed Questions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use What, How, and Tell-me-about openers instead of Is, Do, or Did — closed questions produce yes/no answers that close down exploration.</statement>
        <rationale>Open questions give the speaker control of the answer scope, which surfaces information the interviewer did not know to ask about.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="bad">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["Is the system slow?"
"Do you like the design?"
"Did that cause a problem?"]]></code>
      </example>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["How does the system perform under load?"
"What do you think about the design?"
"How did that affect your team?"]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Empathic Listening Levels">
      <rule>
        <statement>Target Level 5 (Empathic) in high-stakes conversations: understand both the content of what is said and the emotional state of the speaker.</statement>
        <rationale>Levels 1-4 process words; Level 5 processes meaning and feeling. Decision-makers and clients operating under stress communicate 40-60% of their actual concern through emotional register, not explicit words.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Level 1 — Ignoring: not listening at all</item>
        <item>Level 2 — Pretending: "uh-huh" with no engagement</item>
        <item>Level 3 — Selective: hearing only parts while forming a reply</item>
        <item>Level 4 — Attentive: focusing on words, taking notes</item>
        <item>Level 5 — Empathic: understanding feeling AND content</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Reflective Listening Formula">
      <rule>
        <statement>Reflect both content and feeling using the formula: "It sounds like you're [FEELING] because [CONTENT]."</statement>
        <rationale>Naming the feeling signals that you are operating at Level 5; the speaker either confirms (and feels understood) or corrects (providing higher-quality signal).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA["It sounds like you're frustrated because the deadline keeps moving."
"It seems like you're excited about this new approach."
"I hear that you're concerned about the budget implications."]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Mirroring Technique">
      <rule>
        <statement>Mirror by repeating the last 1-3 words of the speaker's sentence as a question — do not add interpretation.</statement>
        <rationale>Mirroring is the lowest-friction technique that produces the highest elaboration rate. It signals attention without leading the speaker toward a particular answer.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Speaker: "We're really struggling with the deployment process."
You: "The deployment process?"
Speaker: [elaborates with root cause and context]]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="Silence Technique">
      <rule>
        <statement>Pause 3-5 seconds after the speaker finishes before responding — do not fill silence immediately.</statement>
        <rationale>People add the most important information after the first pause. Immediate response signals that you were waiting to speak, not listening.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Paraphrasing">
      <rule>
        <statement>Paraphrase at least once per conversation using: "If I understand correctly, you mean..."</statement>
        <rationale>Paraphrasing forces the listener to synthesize rather than just hear, and gives the speaker an explicit correction opportunity before assumptions harden.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="Barriers and Fixes">
      <rule>
        <statement>Identify and neutralize the five common barriers before entering a high-stakes listening situation.</statement>
        <rationale>Each barrier converts a potential Level 5 interaction into Level 3 or lower, degrading information quality and trust.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Planning response — fix: commit to understanding before forming any reply</item>
        <item>Judging — fix: suspend judgment until the speaker has fully finished</item>
        <item>Interrupting — fix: wait 2 seconds after they stop before speaking</item>
        <item>Advising prematurely — fix: ask "Do you want advice or just to vent?" before offering solutions</item>
        <item>Distractions — fix: remove phone, close laptop before the conversation begins</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="Agent Workflow Patterns">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use agents for pre-conversation scaffolding and post-conversation analysis, not live listening execution.</statement>
        <rationale>Active listening is fundamentally reactive to real-time emotional signals. Agents can generate question scripts and annotate transcripts, but cannot adapt in real time to tone or body language.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Two-pass agent workflow for a requirements session.</note>
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Pass 1 (before): Generate RASA-structured question flow for the session goal.
  - Output: Receive-phase opener, Appreciate phrases, Summarize starters, 5 open Ask questions.
  - Constraint: no yes/no questions, no "Is..." or "Do you..." openers.

Pass 2 (after): Annotate transcript with RASA labels.
  - Flag: closed questions used by interviewer
  - Flag: interviewer word-share > 20% in any 3-turn window
  - Flag: Summarize step skipped]]></code>
      </example>
      <reference path="templates/prompt-rasa-question-flow.txt">Prompt template for generating a RASA question flow</reference>
      <reference path="templates/prompt-transcript-annotation.txt">Prompt template for post-session transcript annotation</reference>
      <reference path="templates/speaker-ratio.py">Python snippet to measure interviewer word-share</reference>
    </section>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Generating empathic reflection statements without knowing the interviewee's emotional context.</description>
      <reason>Statements like "It sounds like you're frustrated..." land as condescending or inaccurate when the person was calm. Reflection statements must respond to observed signals, not be pre-generated.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Using "What" or "How" openers for questions that still embed assumptions.</description>
      <reason>"What problems did you have with X?" assumes X caused problems. Check every open question for embedded assumptions before the session.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <antipattern>
      <description>Replacing empathic presence with agent-generated scripts in high-stakes conflict conversations.</description>
      <reason>Using an agent-generated script in a sensitive interpersonal situation risks mechanical delivery that backfires. Active listening is fundamentally reactive; agents cannot adapt to real-time emotional signals.</reason>
    </antipattern>
    <section name="How to Use Agents">
      <p>For generating interview scripts that follow RASA: open questions, paraphrase prompts, silence cues.</p>
      <p>For coaching prep: producing reflective-listening response starters keyed to a specific emotional context.</p>
      <p>For transcript post-processing: identifying where the interviewer talked too much (&gt;20% of words) or used closed questions.</p>
      <p>For requirements gathering support: converting a stakeholder conversation into structured observations using RASA labels.</p>
    </section>
    <section name="Best Practices">
      <list>
        <item>Build the question script before the conversation, but mark questions as "adaptable" — the script is a scaffold, not a reading list.</item>
        <item>For requirements gathering, use Mirroring (repeat last 1-3 words as a question) as a low-effort, high-yield technique; it is the easiest for a human to apply naturally without a script.</item>
        <item>Run the "closed-to-open" conversion on any existing requirement spec questions before a stakeholder session — most specs contain implicit yes/no questions.</item>
        <item>After the conversation, use the transcript annotation pass to identify which RASA steps were skipped (usually Summarize); feed that gap back into coaching notes.</item>
        <item>The "ask for advice or just vent?" technique from the Barriers section prevents misaligned responses; make it a default opener in sensitive conversations.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="AI-Agent Gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Agents generating "open" questions often produce questions that start with "What" or "How" but are still leading ("What problems did you have with X?" implies X caused problems). Check for embedded assumptions.</item>
        <item>Transcript word-count analysis does not account for sentence density — a human may say 20 words but pack in 3x the information of an agent's 60-word turn.</item>
        <item>Empathic reflection statements generated without knowing the interviewee's emotional context can land as condescending or inaccurate ("It sounds like you're frustrated..." when they were calm).</item>
        <item>Human checkpoint required: before acting on a synthesized requirements list derived from a transcript, a human must validate that the RASA annotations match the actual intent of the conversation.</item>
        <item>Silence (the 3-5 second pause) is the most effective active listening tool and the one completely absent from agent-driven text exchanges; compensate with explicit "Is there anything you'd like to add?" prompts.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/prompt-rasa-question-flow.txt" purpose="Prompt to generate a RASA-structured interview script for a given goal"/>
      <template path="templates/prompt-transcript-annotation.txt" purpose="Prompt to annotate a transcript with RASA labels and quality flags"/>
      <template path="templates/speaker-ratio.py" purpose="Python snippet to measure interviewer word-share from a transcript"/>
    </templates>
